  "prompt": "What is the difference between interim and ad interim order?",
  "response": "The terms \"interim order\" and \"ad interim order\" are often used interchangeably in legal contexts, but they can carry slightly different connotations depending on the jurisdiction and context in which they are used. \n\n1. **Interim Order:**\n   - An interim order is a temporary order made by a court that is intended to maintain the status quo or to provide necessary relief until a final decision is made in a case. Interim orders can address various issues, such as injunctions, preservation of property, or other matters requiring immediate attention. The main purpose is to provide temporary relief to one of the parties involved in the litigation.\n\n2. **Ad Interim Order:**\n   - An ad interim order is also a temporary order, but it specifically refers to orders that are issued on a provisional basis, typically in situations that require urgent relief before a final hearing can take place. \"Ad interim\" is a Latin term meaning \"in the meantime\" or \"temporarily.\" These orders are usually granted to ensure that a party's rights are protected until the court can fully hear the case.\n\nIn practice, while both types of orders serve similar functions of providing temporary relief, an \"ad interim\" order may emphasize the urgency of the situation and often takes effect immediately, whereas an \"interim\" order might refer more broadly to any temporary order pending further proceedings. However, the exact distinctions may vary based on legal traditions and the specific legal framework in which the terms are used.",
